<DOC><DOCNO> AP880921-0162 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-88 1950EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-21 0414</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0422</SECOND><HEAD>Seasonably Cool In North, Hot In South</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Cool weather extended across much of the North and the far Weston Wednesday, while the Gulf Coast states and the southern half ofthe Great Plains had hot weather, fairly normal there for the lastfull day of summer.   A warm front over the central Plains helped produce some showersand thunderstorms over Nebraska and western Iowa. Other showers andthunderstorms occurred over Florida, the lower Mississippi Valleyand the Southwest.   Rain moved off the coast of Maine by early afternoon, afteraffecting the Northeastern states for a couple days. But some lightrain and drizzle lingered in western New York state.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT includedthree-tenths of an inch at Green River, Utah, and almost two-tenthsof an inch at Griffiss Air Force Base, at Rome, N.Y.   Cloudy skies and cool temperatures reached from the Great Lakesregion across Minnesota to North Dakota. Temperatures were in the50s and 60s in the early afternoon, with a few 40s in North Dakotaand Minnesota.   Temperatures were close to 90 degrees Wednesday afternoon inFlorida, the Gulf Coast states, Texas and across the Plains as farnorth as Kansas. Orlando, Fla., tied a record high of 94 degrees.Manhattan, Kan., had 92 degrees at 2 p.m. CDT.   The desert Southwest had a break from the heat as mid-afternoontemperatures were only in the 70s to middle 80s.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 45degrees at Devils Lake, N.D., and Jackson, Wyo., to 98 degrees atHarlingen, Texas. The nation's low Wednesday morning was 23 degreesat Truckee, Calif.   With fall officially beginning at 3:29 p.m. EDT on Thursday, thenational forecast called for showers and scattered thunderstormsfrom the region west and northwest of the Rockies across therange's central and southern reaches, the southern high Plains,Nebraska, the middle Mississippi Valley and the lower Ohio Valleyto Wisconsin and Michigan. Scattered showers were expected inwestern New York, and scattered afternoon showers and thunderstormsin central and southern Florida.   High temperatures were predicted to be in the 70s or 80s acrossmuch of the nation, except for 60s in Washington state and near theCanadian border from northern Minnesota to northern New England,and 90s from the southern Great Plains through the lowerMississippi Valley and Gulf Coast states to the south AtlanticCoast states.</TEXT></DOC>